{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180921162750|860576054","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Linda_S\u00e1nchez","to":"Linda S\u00e1nchez"}],"pages":{"409644":{"pageid":409644,"ns":0,"title":"Linda S\u00e1nchez","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-21T17:26:58Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|California|reason=Article needs update|date=July 2018}}\n{{update|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Linda S\u00e1nchez\n|image        = Linda S\u00e1nchez official photo.jpg\n|office       = [[Democratic Caucus Vice-Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Vice Chair of the House Democratic Conference]]\n|leader       = [[Nancy Pelosi]]\n|term_start   = January 3, 2017\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = [[Joseph Crowley|Joe Crowley]]\n|successor    =\n|office1      = Member of the <br/>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[California]]\n|term_start1  = January 3, 2003\n|term_end1    =\n|predecessor1 = [[Ed Royce]]\n|successor1   =\n|constituency1 = {{ushr|CA|39|39th district}} (2003\u201313)<br/>{{ushr|CA|38|38th district}} (2013\u2013present)\n|birth_name   = Linda Teresa S\u00e1nchez\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1969|1|28}}\n|birth_place  = [[Orange, California]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = James Sullivan\n|education    = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|relatives    = [[Loretta S\u00e1nchez|Loretta]] (sister)\n}}\n'''Linda Teresa S\u00e1nchez''' (born January 28, 1969) is an American politician and former [[Labor law in the United States|labor lawyer]] who currently serves as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CA|38}}. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and was first elected to Congress in 2002. She currently serves on the [[Ways and Means Committee]] and is the previous [[ranking member]] on the House [[United States House Committee on Ethics|Ethics Committee]]. In the 114th Congress, she served as the Chair of the [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalhispaniccaucus-lujangrisham.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Hispanic Caucus.|date=|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she was elected by her colleagues to serve as Vice Chair of the House Democratic Caucus for the 115th Congress, the fifth-ranking position in House Democratic leadership. She is the first woman of color ever to be elected to a leadership position in the history of the U.S. Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/rep-linda-sanchez-makes-history-house-leadership-election-n690301|title=Rep. Linda Sanchez Makes History in House Leadership Election|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nS\u00e1nchez was born in [[Orange, California]]. She grew up with six siblings, raised by [[Mexico|Mexican]] immigrant parents in [[Anaheim]], where she attended [[Valencia High School (Placentia, California)|Valencia High School]].<ref>{{cite news | first= David | last= Montgomery | title= Sanchez Sisters Have a Shoe In Each Camp | url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/29/AR2008012903288_pf.html | work= The Washington Post | date= 2008-01-30 | accessdate=2008-04-13 }}</ref> She earned her [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Spanish in 1991 at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and her [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1995 at the [[UCLA School of Law]], where she was an editor of the ''[[Chicano Law Review|Chicano-Latino Law Review]]''.\n\nS\u00e1nchez was an attorney specializing in labor law prior to her public service career. In 1998, she joined the [[International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers]] (IBEW) Local 441 and became a compliance officer. In 2000 she was unanimously elected to the position of Executive Secretary/Treasurer of the [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] Central Labor Council.\n\n==Political campaigns==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2017}}\n'''39th Congressional District (2003 - 2012)'''\n\nS\u00e1nchez started her political career after a new [[California's 39th congressional district|39th congressional district]] was created following the [[United States 2000 Census|2000 Census]] (the old 39th district had very different boundaries). She finished first in a six-person primary for the Democratic Party nomination in March 2002. She won the primaries with 33.5% of the vote, with the second place candidate [[Hector De La Torre|Hector de la Torre]] receiving 29.3%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Linda Sanchez, Jerry Brown Win in California Primary|last=Springer|first=Richard|date=March 15, 2002|work=INDIAWEST|access-date=}}</ref> She went on to win the general elections against Republican Tim Escobar by a 54.9% to 40.8% margin.\n\nShe ran unopposed in the Democratic primaries in 2004. She faced Escobar again in the general election, defeating him by a margin of 60.7% to 39.3%. For the 2006 elections, she defeated two challengers in the primary with 77.8% of the vote, and defeated attorney James L. Andion in the general election.\n\nLinda and her sister, Loretta, became the first pair of sisters to serve together in the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Congress gets its first sister act with Loretta and Linda Sanchez|last=Bunis|first=Dena|date=November 6, 2002|work=Knight Rider Tribune News Service|access-date=}}</ref> Her sister, former Representative [[Loretta Sanchez]], served as a congresswoman from 1996 until she announced her plan to run for U.S. Senate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Loretta Sanchez to Declare Senate Candidacy on Thursday|last=Lazo|first=Alejandro|date=May 13, 2015|work=Dow Jones Institutional News|access-date=}}</ref> She finished second in California's \"top two\" primary, and was defeated by fellow Democrat, state Attorney General [[Kamala Harris]], in the general election in 2016.\n\n'''38th Congressional District (2013 - present)'''\n\nSanchez has represented this district since 2013. In the upcoming election she will be facing Republican Ryan Downing. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/election-results/california-38th-congressional-district/?utm_term=.609e53077e6a|title=Rep. Linda Sanchez, Ryan Downing win California 38th Congressional District primaries|last=|first=|date=August 8, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Linda Sanchez Veterans.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Congresswoman Sanchez participates in Long Beach's Veterans Day celebration.]]\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ethics|Committee on Ethics]]''' (Ranking Member)\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures|Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures]]\n\n===Party leadership and Caucus membership===\n* House Democratic Party Steering and Policy Committee\n* Co-founder of the Labor and Working Families Caucus\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n* '''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe has two committee assignments in the House: the [[United States House Committee on Ethics|Committee on Ethics]] and the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means]]. In 2005, she was appointed Assistant [[Minority Whip]]. She is a member of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus, and is Co-Chair of the Congressional Labor and Working Families Caucus (she co-founded this caucus). She is also a Vice-Chair of the Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus.\n\n==Political Positions==\nIn 2014 [[Project Vote Smart]], using public statements, voting records, and evaluations from special interest groups,<ref name=\"votesmart.org\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/29674/linda-sanchez/|title=Linda S\u00e1nchez's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)|date=2014|work=[[Project Vote Smart|Vote Smart]]|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref> was able to infer the major issues S\u00e1nchez would or not agree upon. Its conclusions, though not officially confirmed by Sanchez, were that S\u00e1nchez:\n\n* supported pro-choice legislation\n* did not support combat operations in Afghanistan\n* supported reducing defense spending to balance budget\n* supported spending to increase economic growth\n* supported federal regulations on greenhouse gas emissions\n* supported the restriction of the purchase and possessions of guns\n* did not support the requirement for illegal immigrants to return to their country of origin before they are eligible for citizenship\n* supported same-sex marriage\n* supported strong social security legislation.<ref name=\"votesmart.org\" />\n\n====Taxes====\nS\u00e1nchez supports a progressive tax system and voted against maintaining reduced tax rates for capital gains and dividends.<ref name=issues>{{cite web| title =Linda Sanchez (Democrat, district 38)| work =On the Issues| url =http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Linda_Sanchez.htm}}</ref>  In addition she was rated a \"Big Spender\" by NTU indicating she generally supports higher tax rates.<ref name=issues/>\n\n====Budget====\nS\u00e1nchez voted against spending prioritizing in the event of the [[debt limit]] being reached. In 2009 she supported both a [[2009 U.S. stimulus package|192 billion dollar anti-recession stimulus package]] and an 825 Billion [[bailout]] fund.<ref name=issues/>  Additional to these, she supported a 15 billion dollar bailout for GM and Chrysler as well as a 60 Billion dollar stimulus package. She voted in 2011 to raise the debt limit to 16.7 trillion dollars.<ref name=issues/> She opposes any move to [[Privatization of Social Security|privatize Social Security]] and supports keeping it strictly federally funded.<ref name=\"issues\" />\n\n====Energy====\nShe opposes new exploration for oil drilling and would remove tax benefits for oil and gas exploration. She has also opposed permits and construction for new oil refineries.<ref name=issues/> She supports tax credits and incentives for investments in renewable energy.<ref name=\"issues\" />\n\n====Government Reform====\nS\u00e1nchez supports lobbyist disclosures for campaign finances as well as requiring [[Dark money|full disclosure of campaign finances]]. She seeks to guarantee free and fair elections.<ref name=issues/>\n\n====Gun Control====\nS\u00e1nchez is pro-gun control and believes in background checks, no fly-no buy, gun control and gun violence research.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=0BB295CEAF424306BCADA379D413C8A3&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1674E84D728DA680/zone%3A|title=Rep. Sanchez Calls for Action on Gun Safety Legislation in Wake of Las Vegas Shooting|last=|first=|date=October 3, 2017|work=Targeted News Service (USA)|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> She seeks to close the [[gun show loophole]] for firearm sales. She believes [[gun manufacturers]] and sellers are accountable and ought to be [[Liability (law)|liable]] for misuse cases by users.<ref name=issues/>\n\n====Healthcare====\nS\u00e1nchez opposes [[Privatization of Medicare|the privatization of Medicare]] in any form, and opposes spending cuts to Medicare. Instead she supports expanding healthcare coverage by a number of programs through federal funding.<ref name=issues/>  She has stated that she believes [[Healthcare as a right|healthcare is a basic right]].<ref name=issues/> However, when asked whether she supports the [[universal health care]] bill HR 676 by Rep. [[John Conyers]], she declined to vote in favor of it,{{vague|\"Nay\", \"Present\", or was she absent? \"Declined to vote in favor\" could mean any of those.|date=July 2018}} citing the need to support the [[Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZrpUrdzj1M&feature=youtu.be|title=Linda Sanchez at April 11, 2017 Town Hall re: HR 676/Universal Healthcare for All|first=|last=Melanie Oringer|date=April 12, 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n====Abortion====\nS\u00e1nchez is [[pro-choice]] and has voted against repealing federal funding for abortions.<ref name=issues/> She opposed legislation to bar transporting minors between states for abortions and making it a crime to harm a fetus in another crime.<ref name=issues/> According to research done by [[Project Vote Smart]], they were able to determine the folowing:<ref name=\"votesmart.org\" />\n\n* S\u00e1nchez \"supported the interests of the [[National Right to Life Committee]] 0 percent in 2010.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/252/rating/5781|title=Rating Group: National Right to Life Committee|date=2010|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n* On October 13, 2011, S\u00e1nchez \"strongly opposed\" the Protect Life Act (H.R. 358).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/646672/|title=Protect Life Act: Floor Speech|last=Sanchez|first=Linda|date=October 13, 2011|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n* S\u00e1nchez supported the interests of [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/1016/rating/5741|title=Rating Group: NARAL Pro-Choice America|date=2010|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n* S\u00e1nchez has voted Nay in many anti-abortion legislation, such as the Abortion Pain Bill, prohibiting Federally Funded Abortion Services, prohibiting Taxpayer Funding of Abortion, the [[Child Interstate Abortion Notification Act]].<ref name=\"votesmart.org\" />\n\n====Civil rights====\nShe was given a 100% rating by the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]], indicating a pro\u2013[[affirmative action]] position.<ref name=\"issues\" /> S\u00e1nchez is a [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]] supporter and opposes [[Discrimination against the LGBT community|discrimination based on sexual orientation or gender]].<ref name=issues/>  On October 4, 2011, S\u00e1nchez made a statement on the LGBT History Month, saying: \"We must continue to strive to end discrimination in the workplace based on sexual orientation and fight so that all Americans have the right to marry and start families with those they love. I remain committed to supporting marriage equality, investments in HIV/AIDS care, treatment and research, and campaigns that take action against bullying in schools.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/646675/|title=Linda S\u00e1nchez Statement on LGBT History Month|last=Sanchez|first=Linda|date=October 4, 2011|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn a letter written on February 9, 2010 to President [[Barack Obama]], then-Speaker of the House [[Nancy Pelosi]], Senator [[Charles Schumer]], S\u00e1nchez explained how \"Currently, U.S. citizens and legal permanent residents may sponsor their spouses (and other immediate family members) for immigration purposes. But, same-sex partners committed to spending their lives together are not recognized as \"families\" under U.S. immigration law and thus do not have this same right.\" and how \"This is unacceptable, and we believe comprehensive immigration reform legislation must include a strong family reunification component inclusive of LGBT families.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/483699/|title=Letter to President Obama, et al.: End Discrimination for Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, And Transgender Binational Families|last=Sanchez|first=Linda|date=February 9, 2010|work=Vote Smart|accessdate=October 25, 2015|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n====Drug policy====\nS\u00e1nchez is pro-[[drug reform]] and supports allowing people with drug-related convictions to receive [[Student loans in the United States|student loans]] if they are deemed to be rehabilitated.<ref name=issues/> She also seeks to [[Expungement|expunge]] records of first-time [[Drug possession|drug offenders]] after probation.<ref name=issues/>\n\n====Environment====\nShe opposes legislation that would bar the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from [[Air quality law|regulating emissions]]. S\u00e1nchez is in favor of higher [[United States emission standards|emission standards]] and establish [[Emissions trading|tradable allowances]].<ref name=issues/>  She supports the [[cash-for-clunkers]] program and seeks to increase [[Public transportation in the United States|public transportation]] and [[Train (public transportation)|trains]] through federally funded projects.<ref name=issues/>\n\nS\u00e1nchez supports the addition of several species to the [[IUCN Red List]] and promotes more extensive nature conservation.<ref name=issues/>\n\n===Davis-Bacon Act===\nFollowing [[Hurricane Katrina]] in late August 2005, President [[George W. Bush]] suspended the [[Davis-Bacon Act]], a 1934 law that requires government contractors to pay prevailing wages. S\u00e1nchez was a very vocal critic of the suspension, and led the fight to reverse it.<ref>[http://www.lindasanchez.house.gov/index.cfm?section=news&article=2005_10_7_4500 Congresswoman Linda T. Sanchez - News<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128030356/http://www.lindasanchez.house.gov/index.cfm?section=news&article=2005_10_7_4500 |date=2005-11-28 }}</ref> S\u00e1nchez eventually won, as Bush reversed himself on October 26, 2005.<ref>[http://www.lindasanchez.house.gov/index.cfm?section=news&article=2005_10_27_4535 lindasanchez.house.gov] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128025920/http://www.lindasanchez.house.gov/index.cfm?section=news&article=2005_10_27_4535 |date=2005-11-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Cyber-bullying prevention===\nIn 2009 and again in 2009, S\u00e1nchez introduced the \"Megan Meier Cyberbullying Prevention Act,\" H.R. 1966, a bill which would criminalize the use of electronic communications if \"the intent is to coerce, intimidate, harass, or cause substantial emotional distress to a person.\"  This bill is a response to the [[suicide of Megan Meier]], a 13-year-old girl whose 2006 suicide was attributed to [[cyber-bullying]] through the [[social networking]] website [[MySpace]]. The bill has drawn criticism from members of the on-line community, legal scholars, and others who have contended that the bill would infringe the constitutional right of [[freedom of speech]].<ref>John Cox, [http://www.networkworld.com/news/2009/050809-bullying-bill.html?hpg1=bn \"Bill would turn Internet flamers into felons\",] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615012523/http://www.networkworld.com/news/2009/050809-bullying-bill.html?hpg1=bn |date=2011-06-15 }} ''[[Network World]]'', May 8, 2009, retrieved May 9, 2009.</ref><ref>Eugene Volokh, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/eugene-volokh/rep-linda-sanchez-defends_b_199556.html \"Rep Linda Sanchez defends outlawing of using blogs, the Web, etc to cause distress\",] ''[[Huffington Post]]'', May 7, 2009, retrieved October 6, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nAfter the Arizona State Legislature passed [[Support Our Law Enforcement and Safe Neighborhoods Act|State Senate Bill 1070]] and after Arizona Governor [[Jan Brewer]] signed it into law, S\u00e1nchez generated controversy<ref name=\"CON\">{{cite web|url=http://abc7.com/archive/7477871/|title=Sanchez under fire for immigration law comment|first=John|last=North|website=ABC7 Los Angeles}}</ref> when she claimed that the law, and similar laws throughout the United States, were the product of white supremacists: \"There's a concerted effort behind promoting these kinds of laws on a state-by-state basis by people who have ties to white supremacy groups. It's been documented. It's not mainstream politics.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/06/03/congresswoman-says-white-supremacist-groups-inspired-arizonas-immigration-law/?test=latestnews | work=Fox News | title=Congresswoman: White Supremacist Groups Behind Arizona Immigration Law | date=June 3, 2010}}</ref> Rep. [[Gary Miller]] called Sanchez's comments \"an outrageous accusation.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ci_15214185 |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229083605/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ci_15214185 |archive-date=February 29, 2012 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Her comments were also condemned by [[Steve Poizner]].<ref name=\"CON\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sanchez Sisters.jpg|right|thumb|190px|Linda and her sister [[Loretta Sanchez]] are the first pair of sisters to serve simultaneously in the [[United States Congress]].]]\nS\u00e1nchez married Jim Sullivan on April 13, 2009, in the district office of Congressman [[John B. Larson]], who introduced the two about two years prior to the wedding.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breakingnews/ci_12247292|publisher=Silicon Valley Mercury News|date=April 28, 2009|title=Rep. Linda Sanchez marries, with baby on the way|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The marriage is the second for S\u00e1nchez, and Sullivan has three sons Brendan, Jack and Seamus from a previous marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=California Rep. Linda Sanchez's baby announcement|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/sunday/la-oe-morrison20-2008nov20,1,3333296.column|first=Patt|last=Morrison|date=November 20, 2008|publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> On May 13, 2009, she became the 8th woman to have given birth while serving in Congress when she gave birth to her first son, Joaquin S\u00e1nchez Sullivan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/2009/05/14/Congresswoman-Sanchez-has-baby-boy/UPI-24591242333103/|title=Congresswoman Sanchez has baby boy|date=May 14, 2009|publisher=[[UPI]]}}</ref>\n\nS\u00e1nchez's father, Ignacio, suffers from [[Alzheimer's disease]], which S\u00e1nchez has cited as a motivation for finding a cure for the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clas.berkeley.edu/Events/fall2008/11-12-08-sanchez/index.html |title=Linda and Loretta S\u00e1nchez:\"A Conversation with the S\u00e1nchez Sisters\" |date=November 12, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615060239/http://clas.berkeley.edu/Events/fall2008/11-12-08-sanchez/index.html |archivedate=June 15, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\nShe is the younger sister of former Congresswoman [[Loretta Sanchez]], who is nine years her senior, making them the first and to date only sister pair to serve in Congress. Linda S\u00e1nchez is considered somewhat more liberal than her older sister. While Loretta began her political career as a moderate [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] before becoming a Democrat, Linda has always been a Democrat. Also, while Loretta was a member of the [[Blue Dog Coalition]] and the [[New Democrat Coalition]], Linda is a member of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]].\n\n[[Stephen Colbert]] interviewed S\u00e1nchez for his 434-part series \"[[Better Know A District]]\" on ''[[The Colbert Report]]''. The segment was aired on [[Comedy Central]] on March 9, 2006.\n\nS\u00e1nchez delivered the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] version of the Democratic Radio Address on May 6, 2006.<ref>http://releases.usnewswire.com/GetRelease.asp?id=65315{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006 S\u00e1nchez won the contest \"Funniest Celebrity in Washington\" during a charity fundraiser.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/07/AR2006100701168.html?nav=rss_opinion/columns | work=The Washington Post | title=Linda Sanchez, the Congresswoman Who Brings Down the House | first1=Amy | last1=Argetsinger | first2=Roxanne | last2=Roberts | date=October 8, 2006 | accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* Linda S\u00e1nchez, Loretta S\u00e1nchez and Richard Buskin, ''Dream in Color: How the S\u00e1nchez Sisters Are Making History in Congress'', Grand Central Publishing (September 2, 2008) {{ISBN|978-0-446-50804-9}}, foreword by [[Nancy Pelosi]]\n\nIn 2008 sister congresswomen Loretta S\u00e1nchez and Linda S\u00e1nchez published the joint memoir ''Dream in Color: How the S\u00e1nchez Sisters Are Making History in Congress''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0446508047 |title=Dream in Color: How the S\u00e1nchez Sisters Are Making History in Congress (9780446508049): Linda S\u00e1nchez, Loretta S\u00e1nchez, Richard Buskin, Nancy Pelosi: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-11}}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' reviewed the book and wrote: \"Linda and Loretta S\u00e1nchez present their compelling story\u2014noteworthy not only for their history-making achievements (including first sisters or women of any relation to serve together in Congress, first woman and person of color to represent a district in Orange County, first Latina on the House Judiciary Committee and first Head Start child to be elected to Congress) but also for its \"American Dream\" aspect\u2014their parents immigrated from Mexico and despite lacking a formal education managed to send their seven children to college. Interweaving childhood vignettes with accounts of serving in Congress, both from California, this refreshing book evades many of the tropes of the typical political memoir\u2014perhaps because these two women are not typical politicians.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Nonfiction Reviews |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6567674.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013082230/http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6567674.html |archive-date=October 13, 2008 |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |date=June 9, 2008 |accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Hispanic and Latino Americans in the United States Congress]]\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://lindasanchez.house.gov/ Congresswoman Linda Sanchez] official U.S. House site\n* [https://voteforlinda.com/ Linda Sanchez for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Linda_Sanchez_%5BD-38%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|lindasanchez}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=S001156 |